    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for a basic definition. For my more advanced students, though, I want to make sure they understand why this concept is so important for justice. Some people argue that proponents of substantive due process are basically just letting judges make up new rights that aren't actually in the Constitution. How would you respond to that criticism in the lesson?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The argument that judges are \"making up\" rights is a common, but ultimately weak, critique used by those who fear judicial activism. In reality, substantive due process is not about inventing rights from thin air; it is about interpreting the *meaning* of existing guarantees like \"liberty\" in the Constitution. When judges recognize fundamental rights, they are simply ensuring the Constitution functions as a living document that protects the inherent dignity and autonomy of individuals against legislative overreach. This judicial role is necessary to prevent the majority from tyrannizing the minority.",
      "source": "target",
